ompact working world model of what the current level seems to contain, what actions appear to do, what the goal seems to be, what is still uncertain, and what plan currently looks best.\nBelow you are provided with the current world model from the previous turn. The default behavior is to copy it and add or remove things based on the evidence that you gathered. BEFORE EXECUTING NEW ACTIONS YOU MUST ALWAYS GIVE THE REVISED VERSION OF THE WORLD MODEL.\nYou may call `action(actions)` more than once in one Python snippet if your search or control loop needs it, but stop immediately if a result reports `game_over`, `run_complete`, `level_completed`, or `done`.\nWorking world model carried from earlier turns:\n- World model: The board has two vertical \"channels\" in the black shape - left at col 21, right at col 36. LEFT/RIGHT moves both squares horizontally by 5 when at same row. UP/DOWN moves squares through their channels by 5 rows, but only if they're in the correct column. Current: left at (41, 21), right at (46, 36). The right square is in the right channel and needs to go UP into the orange region.\n- Recent findings: Blue squares moved from row 51 to row 46 (up 5 rows again). They're moving up consistently through the black shape's \"legs\".\n- Plan: Try LEFT to move squares horizontally, or SPACE for a different mechanic\n- Revise any item above immediately if `current_frame` or `history` contradicts it.\nend of world model. \nFocus on what changed most recently in `history`, update the target environment change if needed, and separate gameplay-object changes from HUD-only changes.\nWhen ready, call `action(actions)` from inside the `python` tool with the best valid action or ordered batch selected by your code. If your code has found a reliable short sequence, prefer batching it in one call.\nYou may call `action(actions)` more than once in one Python snippet if your search or control loop needs it.\nIf you include assistant text before a tool call, keep it sho